California Department of Education
July 31 at 3:45 PM ·

CDE wants to hear from teachers about their successes in distance learning during the last school year. As we support educators in their next phase of virtual instruction, we are tapping the expertise of our practitioners and looking for strategies we can highlight across the state!

We know that last spring all of our educators pivoted quickly to teaching remotely and implemented successful innovations. Please share your experiences with us in this short survey: https://forms.gle/mxq8b3MMbUfFuAsG7

CDE may include what you’ve shared in its next guidance document for school districts.

post_text:
The Ventura County Office of Education is sharing this important update from Ventura County Public Health.

Ventura County continues to see an increase in COVID-19 cases, and we want to ensure that all residents have the information they need to prevent COVID-19 infection.

It’s important to remember that gatherings with anyone other than members of your household are prohibited.

Here are some basic things that you can do to reduce your risk and the risk for others of infection.
1) Wash your hands with soap and water for at least 20 seconds.
2) Don’t touch your nose, mouth or eyes and teach your children to do the same.
3) Maintain 6 ft. distance from others when leaving your house and in public areas.
4) Use face coverings when leaving your home and going out into public areas. This is State mandated.

If you think you have COVID-19 or have been exposed to someone with it, get tested for free. There are various locations throughout the county.

Please go to the website www.venturacountyrecovers.org for all COVID-19 related information for Ventura County.

post_text:
VCOE Statement on Potential Early Reopening of School Campuses

The California Department of Education today announced it is studying options for reopening school campuses after Governor Newsom suggested they could open as early as July or August. Many questions remain about the safety, fiscal and labor implications of reopening campuses before the traditional start of the next school year. For now, there has been no alteration to existing school calendars. The Ventura County Office of Education will be working closely with local school districts and health officials to formulate appropriate plans to return students safely to school in accordance with state guidelines as they are announced.

For the latest information on Ventura County public schools’ response to the coronavirus crisis, including distance learning resources and school meal pickup locations, visit www.vcoe.org.

The California Department of Education today announced it is studying options for reopening school campuses after Governor Newsom suggested they could open as early as July or August. Many questions remain about the safety, fiscal and labor implications of reopening campuses before the traditional start of the next school year. For now, there has been no alteration to existing school calendars. The Ventura County Office of Education will be working closely with local school districts and health officials to formulate appropriate plans to return students safely to school in accordance with state guidelines as they are announced.

For the latest information on Ventura County public schools’ response to the coronavirus crisis, including distance learning resources and school meal pickup locations, visit www.vcoe.org.

post_text:
Please join us for the Ventura County SELPA Transition Fair that is scheduled tomorrow, March 7, from 9am to 12pm at the VCOE conference center in Camarillo.

Just as schools in Ventura County are monitoring the impact of the coronavirus, so are the VCOE and VC SELPA. There are currently no confirmed cases of coronavirus disease in Ventura County and no restrictions on public gatherings ordered by health officials, so the Transition Fair is scheduled to take place as scheduled.

If for any reason we need to reschedule or cancel the Transition Fair, we will communicate this through our website and on our Twitter and Facebook accounts.

Thank you.

post_text: Smokey the Bear visits VCOE's Penfield School in Ventura with friends from the US Forest Service, Los Padres Division to teach kids about fire safety. Students toured the fire trucks, practiced their aim using a fire hose, and reviewed steps to take in case of a fire (stop, drop and roll). By the smiles on the adults’ and students’ faces, you can see this visit was educational and fun!

post_text:
Occupational therapists from around the SELPA shared treatment activities during the OT PT Operational Network meeting.

Marla Rosenblum from Simi shared her professional and personal experiences working with children with special needs. She shared tools from her OT Toolbox and how they serve as communication and collaboration tools with parents and teachers.

Lauren Johnson from Moorpark shared how she uses paper plates and paper bags for all types of activities.

Vera Strang from Moorpark shared how she uses finger puppets, sensory projects and sticker activities with preschoolers.

Robin Goldfinger from Conejo shared how she led teachers through an activity to make a dowel tree activity that teachers used in their classrooms.

Marla led the group through making banners!
text:
Occupational therapists from around the SELPA shared treatment activities during the OT PT Operational Network meeting.

Marla Rosenblum from Simi shared her professional and personal experiences working with children with special needs. She shared tools from her OT Toolbox and how they serve as communication and collaboration tools with parents and teachers.

Lauren Johnson from Moorpark shared how she uses paper plates and paper bags for all types of activities.

Vera Strang from Moorpark shared how she uses finger puppets, sensory projects and sticker activities with preschoolers.

Robin Goldfinger from Conejo shared how she led teachers through an activity to make a dowel tree activity that teachers used in their classrooms.

Marla led the group through making banners!

post_text: Thanks to the ongoing partnership with and generosity from the Ventura County Corvette Club and Central Coast British Car Club, students at VCOE's Penfield School in Ventura will again enjoy a soft plush bear this holiday season. Both car clubs include Penfield School in the Fall Concourses and members generously donate these bears to our students. Our teachers personally select individual bears for each student based on their knowledge of the students’ preferences. The bears are given to the students when Santa visits in December. We so appreciate the support of these local car clubs to create special moments for our students!
